revision.text:
[[File:Tasmania logging 08 Mighty tree.jpg|thumb|right|Named El Grande by the Wilderness Society.]]
'''El Grande''' was a massive ''[[Eucalyptus]]'' (''[[Eucalyptus regnans]]'') in [[Tasmania]] and [[Australia]]'s largest tree. It was located on a ridge in the upper [[River Derwent (Tasmania)|Derwent valley]], adjacent to the World Heritage Area of the Florentine Valley, approximately {{convert|100|km}} from [[Hobart]]. The tree stood {{convert|79|m}} in height, had a girth of {{convert|19|m}}, and a volume of 439 cubic metres. While it was not the tallest tree in Australia, it was considered to be the largest in terms of volume,<ref name="BBC2003">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3306655.stm|title=Forestry officials admit killing biggest tree|date=10 December 2003|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> and the world's biggest-stemmed flowering plant.<ref name="WildernessSociety2007">{{cite web |url=http://www.wilderness.org.au/campaigns/forests/elgrande_4 |title=El Grande, Australia's most massive tree topples |date=7 March 2007 |publisher=The Wilderness Society (Tasmania) Inc |accessdate=18 February 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222043404/http://www.wilderness.org.au/campaigns/forests/elgrande_4 |archivedate=22 December 2010 |df= }}</ref>
Approximately 350 years old,<ref name="BowesBowes2007">{{cite book|last1=Bowes|first1=Bryan B.|last2=Bowes|first2=Bryan G.|title=A colour atlas of trees: biology, ecology, pathologt and conservation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8OCKrvCJhqUC&pg=PA18|accessdate=18 February 2011|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Manson Publishing|isbn=978-1-84076-085-9|pages=18–}}</ref> it was burned in April 2003, and died in December 2003, as the result of catching fire in a burn-off of the debris remaining after the clear-felling of [[old-growth forest]] in the tree's immediate vicinity.<ref name="Lester2010">{{cite book|last=Lester|first=Libby|title=Media and Environment|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XJO0ggLWcP8C&pg=PA152|accessdate=19 February 2011|date=15 November 2010|publisher=Polity|isbn=9780745644028|pages=152–}}</ref><ref name="Darby2003">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/12/10/1070732282970.html|title=Biggest tree killed|last=Darby |first=Andrew |date=December 11, 2003|publisher=[[The Age]]|accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref> Australian forestry officials admitted responsibility for killing the tree.<ref name="BBC2003" /> Its hollow trunk acted like a furnace so that it was cooked from the inside.<ref name="TasmanianTimes2009">{{cite news|url=http://tasmaniantimes.com/index.php?/weblog/article/bartletts-tasmania-house-arrest/show_comments|title=Bartlett’s Tasmania: House Arrest|date=May 14, 2009|publisher=Tasmanian Times|accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref>
The death of the tree, which had already been used as a symbol in the [[The Wilderness Society (Australia)|Wilderness Society]]'s campaign against logging, brought national and international media attention. The destruction of El Grande became a symbol for the destruction of Tasmanian forests.<ref>Lester, p. 148, 152</ref> Scrutiny intensified the use of Tasmania's forests for wood chip exportation, and the processes involved.<ref name="Gianttree2003">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/2953448.stm|title=Giant tree devastated by fire|date=2 June 2003|publisher=BBC|accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref>
In the later half of 2003, Forestry Tasmania decided to remove individual names from the state's giant trees, but later relented.<ref name="The Australian journal of politics and history">{{cite book|title=The Australian journal of politics and history|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kWMtAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=19 February 2011|year=2004|publisher=University of Queensland Press.|page=300}}</ref> Other giant trees in the area of El Grande which are also protected by Forestry Tasmania’s Giant Trees Policy, have since been named [[Centurion (tree)|Centurion]], which was discovered in 2008, and [[Triarius (tree)|Triarius]].<ref name="treelogic.com.au">{{cite web|url=http://treelogic.com.au/facts/2008/10/worlds-tallest-hardwood/ |title=World’s tallest hardwood tree, found in Tasmania |date=14 October 2008 |work=treelogic.com.au |accessdate=19 February 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315153601/http://treelogic.com.au/facts/2008/10/worlds-tallest-hardwood/ |archivedate=15 March 2011 |df= }}</ref> Trees in the vicinity that had been named previously by the Wilderness Society include the Chapel tree and Gandalf's Staff.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Brown, B. |author2=Bayley, V.|year=2003|title=The Valley of the Giants|publisher=The Wilderness Society|isbn = 1-875768-10-6}}</ref>
