'''John William Joseph Williams''' (1929 or 1930 - 29 September 2012) was a Welsh-born computer scientist best known for inventing in 1964 [[heapsort]] and the [[binary heap]] data structure.<ref>{{Citation |first=J. W. J. |last=Williams |author-link=J. W. J. Williams |title=Algorithm 232 - Heapsort |year=1964 |journal=[[Communications of the ACM]] |volume=7 |issue=6 |pages=347–348 |doi= 10.1145/512274.512284}}</ref> He spent the latter part of his career in Canada, moving to [[Kanata, Ontario|Kanata]], [[Ottawa]] in 1972 and working for [[Bell-Northern Research]] and [[Nortel]] before retiring in 1995.

