{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}} {{Use British English|date=June 2012}} '''John James Chipperfield''' (4 March 1894 – 1966) was an English [[association football|football]]er.
Prior to [[World War I]], Chipperfield played for Luton Clarence and Luton Town. He played as a wartime guest for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] during [[World War I]], finishing as the club's top scorer in the [[London Combination]] in both [[1916-17 in English football|1916–17]] and [[1918-19 in English football|1918–19]]. After the war ended he moved to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], making his debut on 30 August 1919,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mehstg.com/aug_30th.htm | title=August 30th | publisher=My Eyes Have Seen the Glory | accessdate=25 June 2012 }}</ref> scoring twice. Chipperfield played for Spurs for two seasons, winning promotion to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] in [[1919-20 in English football|1919–20]] and scoring six goals in total that season.<ref>[http://www.topspurs.com/1920.htm TOPSPURS – The world famous unofficial home of Tottenham Hotspur on the internet<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He made his last appearance in a Spurs shirt on 11 April 1921.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mehstg.com/apr_11th.htm | title=April 11th | publisher=My Eyes Have Seen the Glory | accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> After Tottenham he played for [[Notts County]] (18 league games, 2 goals) and Northfleet before joining [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] in 1923 (3 league games, 0 goals). He played most of his career as an outside left.
