'''Mstislav Romanovich the Old''' ({{lang-uk|Мстислав Романович Старий}}; {{lang-ru|Мстислав Романович Старый}}) (died 1223) was [[Prince]] of [[Pskov]] (1179–?), [[Smolensk]] (1197–?), [[Belgorod Kievsky|Belgorod]] (1206), [[Halych]] (?–?) and [[Grand Prince]] of [[Kiev]] (1212–1223). He was the son of [[Roman of Kiev|Roman Rostislavich]].

Mstislav defeated an invading [[Hungary|Hungarian]] army in 1221. He went to war against the [[Mongols]] of [[Genghis Khan]] in 1223. According to the [[Novgorod Chronicle]], the Mongol commanders Tsigirkan and Teshukan defeated and captured him three days after the [[Battle of the Kalka River]] at a palisade on a nearby hill.

According to the ''[[History of Yuan|Yuan Shi]]'', Jebe ordered a Cathayan commander named Hesimaili to convey Mstislav of Kiev to [[Jochi]], who was then east of the Aral Sea. Jochi ordered Mstislav executed.{{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}

